info.description:
# Introduction

Zenchef API provides all resources relating to bookings necessary for any kind of Zenchef partner

# Overview

Along with the link to this documentation, you will receive:

- an authentication token, necessary to identify your calls on the API. Once connected and on production, each restaurant will have its own auth-token and restaurant id you will have to store and use for the different API calls. The restaurant can find its auth-token in his Zenchef > settings > partners page.
    
- a publisher name, you will have to use in very call modifying a data on Zenchef platform
    

# **Host**

- Production environment : [https://api.zenchef.com/api/v1](https://api.zenchef.com/api/v1)
    
- Test environment : [https://api.preproduction.zenchef.io/api/v1](https://api.preproduction.zenchef.io/api/v1)
    

# Authentication

Every call should provide the following information in header:

- Content-Type: application/json
    
- auth-token: your authentication token
    
- restaurantId: Zenchef restaurant identifier
    
- PublisherName: Your publisher name provided by Zenchef
    
- PublisherModelId: The identifier of the booking on your side
    

# Error Codes

You can expect HTTP error codes. For example:

- 200 OK
    
- 404 Forbidden
    
- 412 Duplicate content

request.description:
This method allows to search through the restaurant bookings using filtering method. You can add as much filters as needed by incrementing a CGI array of filters.

Each filter applied must contain 3 keys : field (the field you're searching on), operator (SQL type filter =,!=,>=,<=,IN,LIKE), value
In case of an IN, you should separate values by commas

Example: 
filters[0][field]=day&filters[0][operator]=>=&filters[0][value]=2016-10-21

The list of searchable fields is :

**day**: Day of the booking

**time**: Time of the booking

**nb_guests**: Number of guests of the booking

**firstname**: Firstname of the guest

**lastname**: Lastname of the guest

**country**: Iso Code of the country of the guest

**phone_number**: Phone number of the guest

**email**: Email of the guest

**comment**: Comment of the guest for the booking

**lang**: Language of the guest on the online booking module

**status**: Status of the booking

**created_at**: Creation date of the booking

**updated_at**: Last updated date of the guest

item.description:
A reservation behaves like some sort of transaction and thus goes through different statuses :

**waiting**: _The end user has registered his information for the booking but the restaurant owner still needs to confirm_

**waiting_customer**: _The restaurant owner is waiting for some feedback from the end user. It might be related to a new time proposal, or a booking imprint for example. We recommand our partenrs and publishers to avoid treating this status (Do not send us a booking in this state, and do not react when you receive this status change). Contact us if needed for more information._ 

**confirmed**: _The restaurant owner has validated the booking and is ok to receive the end user_

**canceled**: _The restaurant owner did not validated the booking issued by the end user_

**refused**: _The end user has refused the new time proposal. You may avoid this parameter as well and treat it has cancelled on your side_

**arrived**: _At least one of the guests has arrived in the restaurant_

**seated**: _All the guests are here, the service has started_

**over**: _The booking is over, guests have left the table_

**no_shown**: _The end user didn't show up to honor his reservation_
